
	stdv: a simple yet usable implementation of a vector<T> in and for C
API:
	* STDV_STD_INIT_CAP: it works a suggestion to create a vector with an initial capacity
	of 64. This macro can be ignored if the user-api needs an exact or greater capacity
	then 64

	* STDV_POS_OF_THE_LAST(vector, offset): it is a safe way of getting the position of last element
	given an offset (if offset is zero it will simply return stdv_size(vector) - 1). This is needed
	since all the api-methods are macros, when those macros are expanded parentheses can mess everything up.

	`offset` cannot be negative because it would be (stdv_size(v) - 1 - (-offset)) which would lead into
	undefined behavior

	* STDV_ALWAYS_POWER_2: by default this macro is disabled. When found it makes stdv to
	always shrink, create and reserve with a capacity power of 2 ignoring the capacity
	given to the method unless such capacity is already a power of 2

	* stdv_create(membsz, cap): creates a new vector of type T with the capacity given (see STDV_ALWAYS_POWER_2)

	* stdv_get(vector, pos): returns the element at `pos`. does not bound-check; reading
	out of bounds is undefined behaviour

	* stdv_get_or(vector, pos, or): like stdv_get, but returns `or` instead if `vector`
	is NULL or `pos` is out of bounds

	* stdv_front(vector): returns the first element. does not check that `vector` is
	non-empty

	* stdv_front_or(vector, or): like stdv_front, but returns `or` if `vector` is NULL
	or empty

	* stdv_back(vector): returns the last element. does not check that `vector` is
	non-empty

	* stdv_back_or(vector, or): like stdv_back, but returns `or` if `vector` is NULL or
	empty

	* stdv_pbeg(vector): returns a pointer to the first element

	* stdv_pbeg_or(vector, or): like stdv_pbeg, but returns `or` if `vector` is NULL or
	empty

	* stdv_pend(vector): returns a pointer to the last element

	* stdv_pend_or(vector, or): like stdv_pend, but returns `or` if `vector` is NULL or
	empty

	* stdv_pget(vector, pos): returns a pointer to the element at `pos`. does not
	bound-check

	* stdv_pget_or(vector, pos, or): like stdv_pget, but returns `or` if `vector` is
	NULL or `pos` is out of bounds

	* stdv_empty(vector): returns true if `vector` is NULL or has no elements

	* stdv_size(vector): returns the number of elements currently stored. `vector`
	cannot be NULL

	* stdv_capacity(vector): returns the number of elements `vector` can currently hold
	before it needs to grow. `vector` cannot be NULL

	* stdv_reserve(vector, newcap): grows `vector` so it can hold at least `newcap`
	elements without reallocating, unless `vector` already has that capacity, in which
	case nothing happens. `vector` can be NULL, in which case a new vector is created
	(see STDV_ALWAYS_POWER_2)

	* stdv_shrink(vector): reallocates `vector` down to a capacity that exactly fits its
	current length (see STDV_ALWAYS_POWER_2). `vector` can be NULL, in which case
	nothing happens

	* stdv_pop_and_free(vector): removes the last element and frees it; only valid when
	`vector`'s element type is itself a pointer, since this macro reinterprets the
	popped element's bytes as a pointer and calls free() on it. returns true if
	something was freed, false if the element was already NULL. this macro does not
	modify the value of the original owner (the variable which called malloc/calloc),
	therefore, once this macro is called, the original variable will be useless since
	it will be pointing to an address already freed

	* stdv_pop_ptr(vector): removes the last element and returns a pointer to it. the
	element is not cleared or freed; the pointer is only valid until the next operation
	that might reallocate `vector`

	* stdv_pop(vector): removes and returns the last element by value

	* stdv_erase(vector, pos): removes the element at `pos`, shifting every later
	element left by one. does not bound-check

	* stdv_put(vector, value): appends `value` to the end of `vector`, growing it if
	needed. `vector` can be NULL, in which case a new vector is created with capacity
	STDV_STD_INIT_CAP. returns the value just appended

	* stdv_put_ptr(vector, value): like stdv_put, but returns a pointer to the appended
	element instead of its value. the pointer is only valid until the next operation
	that might reallocate `vector`

	* stdv_insert(vector, pos, value): inserts `value` at `pos`, shifting every element
	at or after `pos` right by one. grows `vector` if needed. `vector` can be NULL.
	returns the value just inserted

	* stdv_free(vector): frees the vector if it exists and then set `vector` to null. `vector` cannot be a literal
	`NULL` since it would produce a 'NULL = NULL'

